00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:03.000
Would it be relevant to our own development?

00:07:03.000 --> 00:07:05.000
Yeah.

00:07:05.000 --> 00:07:12.000
I would say in my experience working with Python, virtual environments are very, very important and helpful.

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:23.000
So they create this kind of isolated package of, like, your packages, your Python installation,

00:07:23.000 --> 00:07:27.000
and make it a lot easier for whenever you need to reload your project

00:07:27.000 --> 00:07:33.000
or you're sharing your project across environments, like if you're doing it locally or on POSIX Workbench,

00:07:33.000 --> 00:07:36.000
like you saw in the demo.

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:45.000
So, again, my understanding is there are tools that can do the similar sorts of tasks in R.

00:07:45.000 --> 00:07:54.000
One example is the R package, which creates kind of a list of the packages that you're using in a particular project,

00:07:54.000 --> 00:07:55.000
the version.

00:07:55.000 --> 00:08:00.000
And so that way, if you are working with other people on other projects,

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:08.000
you can ensure that everybody has the right packages installed of the right version, things like that.

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:15.000
And there are other tools if you need to, say, control the version of R itself and things like that.

00:08:15.000 --> 00:08:18.000
I would say in my experience, when I first started using R,

00:08:18.000 --> 00:08:22.000
I never really worried about that kind of, like, environment recreation.

00:08:22.000 --> 00:08:27.000
I was working as a solitary data analyst, and I knew exactly what package versions I needed.

00:08:27.000 --> 00:08:35.000
And as things became more collaborative and more complex, as more people got brought into the team,

00:08:35.000 --> 00:08:43.000
then it became very important to make sure that everybody was aligned in terms of their packages and their package version.

00:08:43.000 --> 00:08:50.000
One other thing to mention about Conf is that there is a workshop called What They Forgot to Teach You About R.

00:08:51.000 --> 00:08:55.000
