00:14:38.000 --> 00:14:47.000
Well, I really like using PINs because, well, it enables to do that sort of refresh, as you saw on Connect.

00:14:47.000 --> 00:14:53.000
You PIN the PIN, and then that script that creates that PIN can be automatically refreshed.

00:14:53.000 --> 00:15:03.000
And because it's like the certain file format, it's very small, it's portable, and PIN also allows...

00:15:03.000 --> 00:15:10.000
There are a few functionalities that I actually didn't get into during the demo, but one of the things is like PINs has versioning.

00:15:10.000 --> 00:15:22.000
So say, like, I want to go back to a previous PIN, I can go ahead and call that specific PIN that I need and put it in whatever project that I want.

00:15:22.000 --> 00:15:24.000
I love how versatile PINs are.

00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:29.000
So PINs can be data, they can be models, they can be APIs.

00:15:30.000 --> 00:15:37.000
It's so, so nice in terms of having that flexibility, the things that you want to do.

00:15:37.000 --> 00:15:50.000
Yeah, and then with that flexibility, it's like, as you saw, you can pull the data from an API, clean it up, and you never have to save the CSV somewhere.

00:15:50.000 --> 00:15:54.000
Remember where you put it, remember what version you were using.

00:15:54.000 --> 00:15:56.000
It's all on Connect.

00:15:56.000 --> 00:16:00.000
All, you know, labeled, documented version.

00:16:00.000 --> 00:16:05.000
I use PINs a lot in my projects.

00:16:05.000 --> 00:16:12.000
And I guess I'd just add, like, just to make it really clear, like, you could have it in a CSV, right?

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:17.000
But when you read in a CSV, there's often a lot of things you have to do to get the data exactly the way you want it.

00:16:17.000 --> 00:16:19.000
Like, make sure your dates are written as dates.

00:16:19.000 --> 00:16:23.000
If you've got factors, make sure they've got the right labels or have an order.

00:16:23.000 --> 00:16:25.000
Like, you don't have to worry about that with PINs.

00:16:25.000 --> 00:16:27.000
That's one of the advantages.

00:16:27.000 --> 00:16:35.000
And then the other thing I just mentioned is, if you did go to Shiny, you could have your Shiny app, as it's sort of set up, read from a PIN.

00:16:35.000 --> 00:16:39.000
And that way, it's always going to grab, like, the up-to-date data.

00:16:39.000 --> 00:16:45.000
If you've got that PIN on a schedule, you're going to grab the latest one.

00:16:46.000 --> 00:16:54.000
PINs is one of those packages that it feels like whenever we talk about it, there's so much love for it and a lot of questions about it, too.

