00:20:35.000 --> 00:20:45.000
Say you're working with someone else and you're like, hey, I want you to also be using the latest version of this data all the time.

00:20:45.000 --> 00:20:48.000
You can share your pin with them.

00:20:48.000 --> 00:20:53.000
And they like every time that they're running their project, they have the latest version from the pin.

00:20:53.000 --> 00:20:57.000
And every time you run your project, you're running the latest version from the pin.

00:20:57.000 --> 00:21:01.000
So you can use it in different places with different colleagues.

00:21:01.000 --> 00:21:04.000
Absolutely.

00:21:04.000 --> 00:21:08.000
Awesome. Well, I would love to ask you both.

00:21:08.000 --> 00:21:24.000
What is something that you're really excited about with Quarto or maybe something that came out in the latest release or just something you're excited about for the future?

00:21:24.000 --> 00:21:26.000
I can go first.

00:21:26.000 --> 00:21:27.000
Sure.

00:21:28.000 --> 00:21:34.000
So my personal most excited thing about Quarto is the integration with TypeScript.

00:21:34.000 --> 00:21:37.000
So that's T-Y-P-S-T.

00:21:37.000 --> 00:21:41.000
That's like a new tool open source for generating PDFs.

00:21:41.000 --> 00:21:44.000
It's sort of like a LaTeX competitor.

00:21:44.000 --> 00:21:54.000
And as someone that's always struggled with LaTeX, it's that point in LaTeX where you need to dive into a style file like that.

00:21:54.000 --> 00:21:57.000
I don't really get it. I hate it.

00:21:57.000 --> 00:22:00.000
But TypeScript makes it so much easier.

00:22:00.000 --> 00:22:05.000
The language of types is just so much more familiar to someone like me that's coming from R.

00:22:05.000 --> 00:22:07.000
I expect the same from someone coming from Python.

00:22:07.000 --> 00:22:11.000
But it makes it so much easier to customize a PDF.

00:22:11.000 --> 00:22:19.000
So I think that's going to be really exciting for anyone that has to make PDFs and has to style them in a specific way.

00:22:19.000 --> 00:22:24.000
I think that integration is going to be a game changer.

00:22:24.000 --> 00:22:26.000
It's an in-progress integration.

00:22:26.000 --> 00:22:28.000
So types are still maturing and developing.

00:22:28.000 --> 00:22:30.000
There are a few things that aren't quite there yet.

00:22:30.000 --> 00:22:33.000
And the Quarto integration with it is still developing.

00:22:33.000 --> 00:22:38.000
But I think that's a really exciting place to keep an eye on.

00:22:38.000 --> 00:22:39.000
Awesome.

00:22:39.000 --> 00:22:41.000
Yeah, I've been watching that.

00:22:41.000 --> 00:22:45.000
And I'm really excited to see some examples with it, too.

00:22:45.000 --> 00:22:49.000
Maybe that will be a future workflow demo.

00:22:49.000 --> 00:22:51.000
Isabella, what about you?

00:22:51.000 --> 00:23:01.000
Yeah, I think one thing is just generally the styling in Quarto is so robust.

00:23:01.000 --> 00:23:06.000
And also there's a lot of new exciting things coming up for styling and branding.

00:23:07.000 --> 00:23:15.000
And I love just playing around with different variables and tweaking things to make it look exactly the way I like.

00:23:15.000 --> 00:23:29.000
And so really excited to continue doing that and then also use the new tools available in BSLib or other packages to make the Quarto document of your dreams.

00:23:29.000 --> 00:23:33.000
Thank you so much.

00:23:33.000 --> 00:23:38.000
