00:23:38.000 --> 00:23:48.000
But I did just want to address really quickly one for me was if I could repeat the thing I said about meeting people virtually before PositComp.

00:23:48.000 --> 00:23:57.000
And so I just shared into the chat, if you're thinking about joining us at PositComp, I invite you to join us for next Thursday's Data Science Hangout.

00:23:57.000 --> 00:24:06.000
So the team, the program committee, team handling all the logistics, everybody will be there to answer questions.

00:24:06.000 --> 00:24:12.000
But also as an opportunity to meet other people in the chat who are also going to be there in person.

00:24:12.000 --> 00:24:22.000
I think that was one of my most favorite things about conf last year was seeing people who were friends from the Data Science Hangout getting to meet in person there.

00:24:23.000 --> 00:24:25.000
So just wanted to add that in real quickly.

00:24:25.000 --> 00:24:31.000
And I think something and another important question to address.

00:24:31.000 --> 00:24:39.000
Somebody asked, can you create and run a dashboard without PositConnect as a static HTML, for example?

00:24:39.000 --> 00:24:49.000
Yes. So if you go to the Quarto website, Quarto.org, there is a section on publishing and you can see various options there.

00:24:49.000 --> 00:24:59.000
Yeah. And just to follow it, like if your dashboard doesn't have any shiny components, you can still have sort of widget components like Plotly plots or interactive tables.

00:24:59.000 --> 00:25:09.000
Those do just produce an HTML file. You can host that wherever you want. PositConnect is just a great way to schedule it.

00:25:09.000 --> 00:25:13.000
Awesome. OK, I'll rapid fire another question at you, Isabella.

00:25:13.000 --> 00:25:18.000
How did you get code completion in this when you were writing Python code?

00:25:18.000 --> 00:25:25.000
How did I get code completion? I don't know.

00:25:25.000 --> 00:25:32.000
I just booted up PositWorks VSCode and started using it, so it might be already integrated in there.

00:25:32.000 --> 00:25:39.000
Yeah, my suspicion is probably they have the Python extension automatically loaded for you.

00:25:40.000 --> 00:25:48.000
So if you're using VSCode and you don't have Python code completion, that would be my suggestion to start would be to install the Python extension.

00:25:48.000 --> 00:25:56.000
Sounds good. OK, this is a hard question to pick a favorite, but I thought it'd be interesting to end on.

00:25:56.000 --> 00:26:05.000
Do you have a favorite or a Quarto example that comes to mind that has been most impressive to you?

00:26:05.000 --> 00:26:11.000
I love getting to see the gallery. I know there's an awesome Quarto GitHub repo as well.

00:26:11.000 --> 00:26:24.000
Yeah, I love this website. And usually when folks are like, oh, what kind of website can I create with Quarto?

00:26:24.000 --> 00:26:27.000
I point them to this one. It's World World Data Science.

00:26:27.000 --> 00:26:35.000
And I just think it's an amazing showcase of just how custom you can make your Quarto website look.

00:26:35.000 --> 00:26:39.000
And the creator of this website actually gave a talk in the last PositCon.

00:26:39.000 --> 00:26:49.000
So the video recording is on YouTube to hear about his journey from journalist to programmer.

00:26:49.000 --> 00:26:54.000
That's awesome. I just shared that one in the chat.

00:26:54.000 --> 00:27:01.000
I'm really struggling to think of a particular one. There's so many.

00:27:01.000 --> 00:27:13.000
There's just so many examples. I think some of the most public ones are websites.

00:27:13.000 --> 00:27:17.000
You don't have to pick one.

00:27:17.000 --> 00:27:22.000
Yeah, but one thing I've been doing with that. So I'm going to be teaching the Quarto websites workshop at comp.

00:27:22.000 --> 00:27:26.000
So I've been looking at a lot of examples of what people are doing with Quarto.

00:27:26.000 --> 00:27:33.000
And I'm still sort of amazed. One of the things that really amazes me is the things people can do with these things called listings.

00:27:33.000 --> 00:27:39.000
So a listing in a Quarto website is essentially a way to generate a page automatically from some content.

00:27:40.000 --> 00:27:46.000
And that content could be other Quarto files. It could be just some YAML, some structured data.

00:27:46.000 --> 00:27:50.000
And people just do really amazing things with these.

00:27:50.000 --> 00:27:55.000
The sort of classic thing is you create a blog. A blog is just a listing.

00:27:55.000 --> 00:28:03.000
But people do really cool things to showcase their projects or to list out all the talks they're giving.

00:28:04.000 --> 00:28:09.000
It's like one of those Quarto features that you read about on the website and you're like, oh yeah, I get it.

00:28:09.000 --> 00:28:13.000
And then people have run with it and they've done some really, really beautiful, amazing things.

00:28:15.000 --> 00:28:19.000
I love that too. I won't say that my example is beautiful.

00:28:19.000 --> 00:28:25.000
But I did use that listings functionality to build a data science community builder site.

00:28:25.000 --> 00:28:30.000
And so I was pulling together a bunch of resources from other community builders.

00:28:30.000 --> 00:28:34.000
And I found the listings site to be really helpful for that.

